#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:150
msgid "Compatibility notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:153
msgid "``linalg.eig`` and ``linalg.eigvals`` now always return complex arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:155
msgid ""
"Previously, the return values depended on whether the eigenvalues happen to "
"lie on the real line (which, for a general, non-symmetric matrix, is not "
"guaranteed)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:158
msgid ""
"The change makes consistent what was a value-dependent result. To retain the "
"previous behavior, do::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:161
msgid ""
"w = eigvals(a)\n"
"if np.any(w.imag == 0):  # this is what NumPy used to do\n"
"    w = w.real"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:165
msgid ""
"If your matrix is symmetrix/hermitian, use ``eigh`` and ``eigvalsh`` instead "
"of ``eig`` and ``eigvals``. These are guaranteed to return real values. A "
"common case is covariance matrices, which are symmetric and positive "
"definite by construction."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:170
msgid "(`gh-30411 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30411>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:173
msgid "MSVC support"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:174
msgid ""
"NumPy now requires minimum MSVC 19.35 toolchain version on Windows "
"platforms. This corresponds to Visual Studio 2022 version 17.5 Preview 2 or "
"newer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:178
msgid "(`gh-30489 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30489>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:181
msgid "Cython support"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:183
msgid ""
"NumPy's Cython headers (accessed via ``cimport numpy``) now require Cython "
"3.0 or newer to build. If you try to compile a project that depends on "
"NumPy's Cython headers using Cython 0.29 or older, you will see a message "
"like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:190
msgid ""
"Error compiling Cython file:\n"
"------------------------------------------------------------\n"
"...\n"
"# versions.\n"
"#\n"
"# See __init__.cython-30.pxd for the real Cython header\n"
"#\n"
"\n"
"DEF err = int('Build aborted: the NumPy Cython headers require Cython 3.0.0 "
"or newer.')\n"
"  ------------------------------------------------------------\n"
"\n"
"  /path/to/site-packages/numpy/__init__.pxd:11:13: Error in compile-time "
"expression: ValueError: invalid literal for int() with base 10: 'Build "
"aborted: the NumPy Cython headers require Cython 3.0.0 or newer.'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:204
msgid ""
"Note that the invalid integer is not a bug in NumPy - we are intentionally "
"generating this error to avoid triggering a more obscure error later in the "
"build when an older Cython version tries to use a Cython feature that was "
"not available in the old Cython version."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:209
msgid "(`gh-30770 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30770>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:212
msgid "``numpy.where`` no longer truncates Python integers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:214
msgid ""
"Previously, if the ``x`` or ``y`` argument of ``numpy.where`` was a Python "
"integer that was out of range of the output type, it would be silently "
"truncated. Now, an `OverflowError` will be raised instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:218
msgid ""
"This change also applies to the underlying C API function ``PyArray_Where``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:220
msgid "(`gh-30803 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30803>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:223
msgid "Default memory allocator change"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:224
msgid ""
"NumPy now uses ``PyMem_RawMalloc`` and ``PyMem_RawFree`` as the default "
"memory allocator, instead of system's ``malloc`` and ``free`` directly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:227
#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:356
msgid "(`gh-30846 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30846>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:230
msgid "``from_dlpack`` raises ``BufferError`` instead of ``RuntimeError``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:232
msgid ""
"``np.from_dlpack`` now raises ``BufferError`` instead of ``RuntimeError`` "
"when the incoming DLPack tensor has an unsupported device, dtype, or exceeds "
"the maximum number of dimensions. This aligns with the DLPack and Array API "
"specifications, which recommend ``BufferError`` for data that cannot be "
"imported."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:238
msgid "(`gh-30937 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30937>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:242
msgid "C API changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:244
msgid ""
"Added ``PyDataType_TYPE``, ``PyDataType_KIND``, ``PyDataType_BYTEORDER`` and "
"``PyDataType_TYPEOBJ`` accessor macros to the C API. Together with the other "
"accessor macros added for the NumPy 2.0 transition, these allow accessing "
"the fields of ``PyArray_Descr`` structs without any direct field accesses."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:249
msgid "(`gh-30994 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30994>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:252
msgid "``PyArray_DescrFromScalar`` now preserves parametric dtype information"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:253
msgid ""
"``PyArray_DescrFromScalar`` now correctly returns the full dtype descriptor "
"for scalars of user-defined parametric data types, including any dtype "
"parameters. Previously, parameters were silently discarded, which could "
"cause incorrect results in operations like ``astype`` on scalar objects. "
"Internally, the function now delegates to ``discover_descr_from_pyobject``, "
"which handles parametric dtypes correctly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:260
msgid "(`gh-31067 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/31067>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:264
msgid "New Features"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:267
msgid "Pixi package definitions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:268
msgid ""
"Pixi package definitions have been added for different kinds of from-source "
"builds of NumPy. These can be used in downstream Pixi workspaces via the "
"``pixi-build`` feature."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:272
msgid ""
"Definitions for both ``default`` and AddressSanitizer-instrumented "
"(``asan``) builds are available in the source code under the ``pixi-packages/"
"`` directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:276
msgid "``linux-64`` and ``osx-arm64`` platforms are supported."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:278
msgid "(`gh-30381 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30381>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:281
msgid "``numpy.ndarray`` now supports structural pattern matching"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:282
msgid ""
"`numpy.ndarray` and its subclasses now have the ``Py_TPFLAGS_SEQUENCE`` flag "
"set, enabling structural pattern matching (PEP 634) with ``match``/``case`` "
"statements. This also enables Cython to optimize integer indexing "
"operations. See :ref:`arrays.ndarray.pattern-matching` for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:287
msgid "(`gh-30653 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30653>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:291
msgid "Improvements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:293
msgid ""
"For ``f2py``, the behaviour of ``intent(inplace)`` has improved. Previously, "
"if an input array did not have the right dtype or order, the input array was "
"modified in-place, changing its dtype and replacing its data by a corrected "
"copy.  Now, instead, the corrected copy is kept a separate array, which, "
"after being passed and presumably modified by the fortran routine, is copied "
"back to the input routine.  The above means one no longer has the risk that "
"pre-existing views or slices of the input array start pointing to "
"unallocated memory (at the price of increased overhead for the write-back "
"copy at the end of the call)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:304
msgid ""
"A potential problem would be that one might get very different results if "
"one, e.g., previously passed in an integer array where a double array was "
"expected: the writeback to integer would likely give wrong results.  To "
"avoid such situations, ``intent(inplace)`` will now only allow arrays that "
"have equivalent type to that used in the fortran routine, i.e., ``dtype."
"kind`` is the same. For instance, a routine expecting double would be able "
"to receive float, but would raise on integer input."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:313
msgid "(`gh-29929 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/29929>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:316
msgid "``f2py`` modules now show allocatable arrays in ``dir()``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:317
msgid ""
"Allocatable module variables wrapped by ``f2py`` now appear in ``dir()`` "
"output, matching their accessibility by name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:320
msgid "(`gh-30965 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30965>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:324
msgid "Performance improvements and changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:327
msgid "Improved performance of ``numpy.searchsorted``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:328
msgid ""
"The C++ binary search implementation used by ``numpy.searchsorted`` now has "
"a much better performance when searching for multiple keys. The new "
"implementation batches binary search steps across all keys to leverage cache "
"locality and out-of-order execution. Benchmarks show the new implementation "
"can be up to 20 times faster for hundreds of thousands keys while single-key "
"performance remains comparable to previous versions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:335
msgid "(`gh-30517 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30517>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:338
msgid "Improved scaling of ufuncs on free-threading"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:340
msgid ""
"NumPy's ufuncs now scale significantly better on free-threading builds of "
"CPython due to the following optimizations:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:343
msgid ""
"**Lock-free dispatch table:** The ufuncs dispatch table is now implemented "
"as a lock-free concurrent hash map, allowing multiple threads to call ufuncs "
"without contention."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:347
msgid ""
"**Immortal shared objects:** Certain shared objects, such as global memory "
"handlers, have been made immortal. This effectively reduces reference "
"counting contention across threads."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:351
msgid ""
"**Optimized memory allocation:** NumPy now utilizes ``PyMem_RawMalloc`` and "
"``PyMem_RawFree`` for memory allocation. On Python 3.15 and newer, this "
"leverages ``mimalloc`` and significantly reduces memory allocation overhead "
"in multi-threaded workloads."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:360
msgid "Typing improvements and changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:363
msgid ""
"``numpy.linalg`` typing improvements and preliminary shape-typing support"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:364
msgid ""
"Input and output dtypes for ``numpy.linalg`` functions are now more precise. "
"Several of these functions also gain preliminary shape-typing support while "
"remaining backward compatible. For example, the return type of ``numpy."
"linalg.matmul`` now depends on the shape-type of its inputs, or fall back to "
"the backward-compatible return type if the shape-types are unknown at type-"
"checking time. Because of limitations in Python's type system and current "
"type-checkers, shape-typing cannot cover every situation and is often only "
"implemented for the most common lower-rank cases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:371
msgid "(`gh-30480 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30480>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:374
msgid "``numpy.ma`` typing annotations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:375
msgid ""
"The ``numpy.ma`` module is now fully covered by typing annotations. This "
"includes annotations for masked arrays, masks, and various functions and "
"methods. With this, NumPy has achieved 100% typing coverage across all its "
"submodules."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:379
msgid "(`gh-30566 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/30566>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:383
msgid "Changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:386
msgid "``numpy.ctypeslib.as_ctypes`` now does not support scalar types"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:387
msgid ""
"The function ``numpy.ctypeslib.as_ctypes`` has been updated to only accept "
"``numpy.ndarray``. Passing a scalar type (e.g., ``numpy.int32(5)``) will now "
"raise a ``TypeError``. This change was made to avoid the issue `gh-30354 "
"<https://github.com/numpy/numpy/issues/30354>`__ and to enforce the readonly "
"nature of scalar types in NumPy. The previous behavior relied on "
"undocumented implicit temporary arrays and was not well-defined. Users who "
"need to convert scalar types to ctypes should first convert them to an array "
"(e.g., ``numpy.asarray``) before passing them to ``numpy.ctypeslib."
"as_ctypes``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:397
msgid "``__array_interface__`` changes on scalars"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/notes-towncrier.rst:398
msgid ""
"Scalars now export the ``__array_interface__`` directly rather than "
"including an array copy as a ``__ref`` entry. This means that scalars are "
"now exported as read-only while they previously exported as writeable. The "
"path via ``__ref`` was undocumented and not consistently used even within "
"NumPy itself."
msgstr ""

